          "id": "medquad-chunk-f141013ed0928877",
          "title": "What is (are) Achondrogenesis ?",
          "content": "Achondrogenesis is a group of serious genetic disorders that are present from birth and have a significant impact on how cartilage and bone develop in the body. Infants who are born with achondrogenesis often exhibit a smaller overall body size, with notably shorter arms and legs. Additionally, they may have various skeletal abnormalities that can lead to severe health complications, which can be life-threatening.\nThere are at least three recognized forms of achondrogenesis, which are classified as type 1A, type 1B, and type 2. Each of these types has unique characteristics that help medical professionals distinguish between them. For instance, the signs and symptoms, the way the disorder is inherited, and the results from imaging studies such as X-rays, tissue analysis, and genetic testing all play a role in identifying the specific type of achondrogenesis.\n- Type 1A and type 1B are inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a child to be affected by either type, both parents must carry the gene associated with the disorder. In the case of type 1B, it may be linked to mutations in a specific gene known as SLC26A2.\n- On the other hand, type 2 achondrogenesis is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. This means that only one parent needs to pass on the gene for the child to be affected. Type 2 is caused by new mutations that occur in the COL2A1 gene, which can happen spontaneously.\nUnderstanding the different types of achondrogenesis is essential for healthcare providers as it aids in accurate diagnosis and helps in planning appropriate treatment strategies. This knowledge can also provide families with important information regarding the condition and its implications for their child's health and development.\nContext recap: Achondrogenesis is a group of serious genetic disorders that are present from birth and have a significant impact on how cartilage and bone develop in the body. Infants who are born with achondrogenesis often exhibit a smaller overall body size, with notably shorter arms and legs. Additionally, they may have various skeletal abnormalities that can lead to severe health complications, which can be life-threatening. There are at least three recognized forms of achondrogenesis, which are classified as type 1A, type 1B, and type 2.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Achondrogenesis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Achondrogenesis is a group of serious genetic disorders that are present from birth and have a significant impact on how cartilage and bone develop in the body. Infants who are born with achondrogenesis often exhibit a smaller overall body size, with notably shorter arms and legs. Additionally, they may have various skeletal abnormalities that can lead to severe health complications, which can be life-threatening. There are at least three recognized forms of achondrogenesis, which are classified as type 1A, type 1B, and type 2.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Achondrogenesis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
