          "id": "medquad-chunk-14b529892a016a82",
          "title": "What is (are) Achondrogenesis type 2 ?",
          "content": "Achondrogenesis type 2 is a serious genetic disorder that affects how cartilage and bone develop in the body. This condition is present from birth and can lead to significant health challenges for infants. Babies born with achondrogenesis type 2 often have a smaller body size compared to other infants, and they may have short arms and legs. Additionally, they can exhibit various skeletal abnormalities, which can result in life-threatening complications.\nThere are three main types of achondrogenesis: type 1A, type 1B, and type 2. Each type has its own unique characteristics, including specific signs and symptoms, how the disorder is inherited, and the findings from medical imaging tests like X-rays, as well as tissue and genetic analyses.\nTypes 1A and 1B are inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to express the disorder. Type 1B has been linked to mutations in a gene known as SLC26A2. On the other hand, achondrogenesis type 2 is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. This means that only one copy of the mutated gene is sufficient for a child to be affected by the disorder. Type 2 is often caused by new mutations that occur in the COL2A1 gene, which is crucial for the production of collagen, a protein that helps form cartilage and bone.\nUnderstanding these distinctions is important for medical professionals and families affected by achondrogenesis, as it can guide diagnosis, management, and potential treatment options. Genetic counseling may also be beneficial for families to understand the risks of inheritance and the implications for future pregnancies.\nContext recap: Achondrogenesis type 2 is a serious genetic disorder that affects how cartilage and bone develop in the body. This condition is present from birth and can lead to significant health challenges for infants. Babies born with achondrogenesis type 2 often have a smaller body size compared to other infants, and they may have short arms and legs. Additionally, they can exhibit various skeletal abnormalities, which can result in life-threatening complications.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Achondrogenesis type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Achondrogenesis type 2 is a serious genetic disorder that affects how cartilage and bone develop in the body. This condition is present from birth and can lead to significant health challenges for infants. Babies born with achondrogenesis type 2 often have a smaller body size compared to other infants, and they may have short arms and legs. Additionally, they can exhibit various skeletal abnormalities, which can result in life-threatening complications.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Achondrogenesis type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
