          "id": "medquad-chunk-7f7874184a774fc8",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Achondroplasia ?",
          "content": "Achondroplasia is a genetic condition that affects bone growth and can lead to a variety of signs and symptoms. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for early diagnosis and management. One of the notable symptoms in infants is apnea, which refers to episodes where breathing stops for more than 15 seconds. This can be alarming for parents and caregivers. While snoring is often associated with sleep apnea, it's important to recognize that many children with achondroplasia may snore without having significant breathing issues. However, if a child exhibits signs of obstructive apnea, such as increased retraction of the chest, choking during sleep, or frequent awakenings at night, it may indicate a need for further evaluation. In such cases, doctors may recommend lung and sleep studies to assess the child's breathing patterns more closely.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that compiles information on various signs and symptoms associated with different medical conditions, including achondroplasia. According to HPO, several common signs are frequently observed in individuals with achondroplasia. For instance, abnormalities of the metaphyses and ribs are seen in approximately 90% of patients. Other symptoms that may occur include:\n- Anteverted nares (90%)\n- Brachydactyly syndrome (90%)\n- Depressed nasal bridge (90%)\n- Frontal bossing (90%)\n- Genu varum (bowed legs) (90%)\n- Hyperlordosis (excessive inward curvature of the spine) (90%)\n- Limb undergrowth (90%)\n- Macrocephaly (larger than average head size) (90%)\n- Skeletal dysplasia (90%)\nIn addition to these common symptoms, there are other signs that may occur in about 50% of patients, including:\n- Abnormal form of the vertebral bodies\n- Abnormality of the teeth\n- Apnea\n- Conductive hearing impairment\n- Hyperhidrosis (excessive sweating)\n- Intrauterine growth retardation\n- Joint hypermobility\n- Kyphosis (curvature of the spine)\n- Long thorax\n- Malar flattening (flattened cheekbones)\n- Muscular hypotonia (decreased muscle tone)\n- Narrow chest\n- Obesity\n- Ventriculomegaly (enlarged brain ventricles)\nSome symptoms are less common, occurring in about 7.5% of patients, such as:\n- Acanthosis nigricans (dark, velvety patches of skin)\n- Elbow dislocation\n- Hydrocephalus (accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid in the brain)\n- Neurological speech impairment\n- Spinal canal stenosis (narrowing of the spinal canal)\n- Sudden cardiac death\nAchondroplasia is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that only one copy of the mutated gene from an affected parent can cause the condition in their child. This genetic aspect is important for understanding the risk of passing the condition to future generations.\nThe information regarding the frequency of these signs and symptoms is gathered from various studies and databases, including Orphanet, which focuses on rare diseases. The frequency is typically expressed as a percentage, indicating how many patients in a study exhibited a particular symptom. For example, if a symptom is reported in 25 out of 25 patients, it suggests that all individuals in that study experienced that symptom. However, it's essential to note that these frequencies can vary depending on the specific population studied and the methods used in the research. In some cases, there may not be enough data available to provide a frequency estimate, which could indicate that the symptom is either rare or not well-documented in the literature.\nIn conclusion, recognizing the signs and symptoms of achondroplasia is vital for timely intervention and support. If you suspect that a child may have achondroplasia or if they exhibit any concerning symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for a thorough evaluation and guidance. Early diagnosis and management can significantly improve the quality of life for individuals with this condition.\nContext recap: Achondroplasia is a genetic condition that affects bone growth and can lead to a variety of signs and symptoms. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for early diagnosis and management. One of the notable symptoms in infants is apnea, which refers to episodes where breathing stops for more than 15 seconds. This can be alarming for parents and caregivers.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Achondroplasia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Achondroplasia is a genetic condition that affects bone growth and can lead to a variety of signs and symptoms. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for early diagnosis and management. One of the notable symptoms in infants is apnea, which refers to episodes where breathing stops for more than 15 seconds. This can be alarming for parents and caregivers.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Achondroplasia ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
