          "id": "medquad-chunk-1cd5ff2d3a1da5ca",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of ADULT syndrome ?",
          "content": "What are the signs and symptoms of ADULT syndrome? ADULT syndrome is a rare genetic condition that can affect various parts of the body. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) provides a comprehensive list of signs and symptoms that are commonly associated with this syndrome. Understanding these symptoms can help in identifying the condition and seeking appropriate medical care. Below is a detailed table that outlines some of the symptoms along with their approximate occurrence rates among individuals diagnosed with ADULT syndrome:\n- **Abnormality of the eye**: This symptom is observed in about 90% of patients. It can include various eye-related issues that may affect vision.\n- **Abnormality of the fingernails**: Approximately 90% of individuals with ADULT syndrome may experience changes in their fingernails, which can appear different from typical nails.\n- **Abnormality of the toenails**: Similar to fingernails, about 90% of patients may also have unusual toenails.\n- **Dry skin**: This is a common symptom, affecting around 90% of those with the syndrome, leading to skin that may feel rough or flaky.\n- **Fine hair**: Many individuals, about 90%, may have hair that is thinner or finer than average.\n- **Finger syndactyly (webbed fingers)**: This occurs in approximately 90% of patients, where two or more fingers are fused together.\n- **Freckling**: About 90% of individuals may develop freckles, which are small brown spots on the skin.\n- **Melanocytic nevus (mole)**: This symptom is also seen in about 90% of patients, referring to moles that can appear on the skin.\n- **Skin ulcer**: Around 90% of individuals may experience skin ulcers, which are open sores that can develop on the skin.\n- **Split foot**: This is another symptom affecting about 90% of patients, where the foot may have a split appearance.\n- **Thin skin**: Approximately 90% of individuals may have skin that is thinner than normal, which can be more fragile.\n- **Toe syndactyly (webbed toes)**: Similar to finger syndactyly, about 90% of patients may have webbed toes.\n- **Abnormality of dental morphology**: This affects about 50% of individuals, indicating that their teeth may have unusual shapes or sizes.\n- **Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nipples**: This condition, affecting around 50% of patients, refers to underdeveloped or absent nipples.\n- **Breast aplasia**: About 50% of individuals may experience a lack of breast tissue development.\n- **Prominent nasal bridge**: This feature is seen in about 7.5% of patients, where the bridge of the nose appears more pronounced.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology gathers this information from various reputable sources, including Orphanet, a European database dedicated to rare diseases. The frequency of each symptom is typically presented as an estimate, indicating the percentage of patients who exhibit that particular symptom. In some cases, this frequency may be expressed as a fraction. For instance, a frequency of 25/25 means that in a study involving 25 individuals, all of them were found to have that specific symptom. It is crucial to understand that these frequencies are based on specific studies and may differ if another group of patients is examined. Additionally, there may be instances where information about the frequency of certain symptoms is not available, which could suggest that these symptoms are either rare or more common than expected. Understanding these symptoms is vital for early diagnosis and management of ADULT syndrome, and it highlights the importance of ongoing research in the field of rare diseases.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of ADULT syndrome? ADULT syndrome is a rare genetic condition that can affect various parts of the body. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) provides a comprehensive list of signs and symptoms that are commonly associated with this syndrome. Understanding these symptoms can help in identifying the condition and seeking appropriate medical care.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of ADULT syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of ADULT syndrome? ADULT syndrome is a rare genetic condition that can affect various parts of the body. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) provides a comprehensive list of signs and symptoms that are commonly associated with this syndrome. Understanding these symptoms can help in identifying the condition and seeking appropriate medical care.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of ADULT syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
