          "id": "medquad-chunk-c44ed95fe31549f3",
          "title": "What causes Adult-onset Still's disease ?",
          "content": "What causes adult-onset Still's disease? The exact cause of adult-onset Still's disease remains a mystery that researchers are actively trying to solve. Some scientists propose that this condition may be triggered by a virus or another type of infectious agent, which means that an infection could potentially set off the symptoms associated with this disease. On the other hand, there are also researchers who believe that adult-onset Still's disease might be linked to an autoimmune response. In this scenario, the body's immune system mistakenly identifies its own healthy tissues as harmful and attacks them, leading to the symptoms of the disease. Despite these theories, it is important to note that, as of now, there is no conclusive evidence that definitively proves or disproves either of these ideas. This highlights the need for further research to better understand the underlying causes of adult-onset Still's disease and to develop effective treatments for those affected by it.\nContext recap: What causes adult-onset Still's disease? The exact cause of adult-onset Still's disease remains a mystery that researchers are actively trying to solve. Some scientists propose that this condition may be triggered by a virus or another type of infectious agent, which means that an infection could potentially set off the symptoms associated with this disease. On the other hand, there are also researchers who believe that adult-onset Still's disease might be linked to an autoimmune response.\nContext recap: What causes adult-onset Still's disease? The exact cause of adult-onset Still's disease remains a mystery that researchers are actively trying to solve. Some scientists propose that this condition may be triggered by a virus or another type of infectious agent, which means that an infection could potentially set off the symptoms associated with this disease. On the other hand, there are also researchers who believe that adult-onset Still's disease might be linked to an autoimmune response.\nWhy this matters: What causes Adult-onset Still's disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
