          "id": "medquad-chunk-8a26a3a010879722",
          "title": "What is (are) Andermann syndrome ?",
          "content": "Andermann syndrome (AS) is a rare genetic disorder that significantly impacts the functioning of nerves, particularly those that control muscle movement and sensation. This condition can lead to a variety of challenges for individuals affected by it. One of the most common symptoms is muscle weakness, which can make it difficult for individuals to coordinate their movements effectively. This weakness is often accompanied by a condition known as hypotonia, where the muscle tone is lower than normal, leading to difficulties in maintaining posture and balance. Additionally, many individuals with Andermann syndrome experience a loss of sensation in their limbs, which can affect their ability to feel touch, pain, or temperature. Tremors, or involuntary shaking movements, are also a common symptom of this disorder.\nA notable feature of Andermann syndrome is the presence of agenesis of the corpus callosum, a condition where the corpus callosum—the part of the brain that connects the left and right hemispheres—is either absent or malformed. This can lead to further complications in brain function and coordination. As individuals with Andermann syndrome grow older, they may face challenges with walking, and many may lose the ability to walk altogether by their teenage years.\nIn addition to physical symptoms, Andermann syndrome can also affect cognitive abilities. Some individuals may experience intellectual disabilities, which can impact learning and daily functioning. Seizures are another potential symptom, which can vary in frequency and severity. Furthermore, individuals with this syndrome may exhibit various atypical physical features, which can include differences in facial structure or other body characteristics.\nPsychiatric symptoms may also be present, adding another layer of complexity to the condition. These can include mood disorders or difficulties with social interactions. Other physical issues may arise, such as contractures (tightening of muscles or tendons), scoliosis (curvature of the spine), and problems with cranial nerves, which can lead to facial muscle weakness, drooping eyelids (ptosis), and difficulties in eye movement (gaze palsy).\nAndermann syndrome is caused by mutations in the SLC12A6 gene, which plays a crucial role in nerve function. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that both parents must carry and pass on the mutated gene for their child to be affected. While Andermann syndrome is associated with a shortened life expectancy, many individuals with this condition can live into adulthood, and with appropriate support and care, they can lead fulfilling lives.\nContext recap: Andermann syndrome (AS) is a rare genetic disorder that significantly impacts the functioning of nerves, particularly those that control muscle movement and sensation. This condition can lead to a variety of challenges for individuals affected by it. One of the most common symptoms is muscle weakness, which can make it difficult for individuals to coordinate their movements effectively. This weakness is often accompanied by a condition known as hypotonia, where the muscle tone is lower than normal, leading to difficulties in maintaining posture and balance.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Andermann syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Andermann syndrome (AS) is a rare genetic disorder that significantly impacts the functioning of nerves, particularly those that control muscle movement and sensation. This condition can lead to a variety of challenges for individuals affected by it. One of the most common symptoms is muscle weakness, which can make it difficult for individuals to coordinate their movements effectively. This weakness is often accompanied by a condition known as hypotonia, where the muscle tone is lower than normal, leading to difficulties in maintaining posture and balance.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Andermann syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
