          "id": "medquad-chunk-c7df704e54ee2bf0",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Androgen insensitivity syndrome ?",
          "content": "Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a condition that affects how the body responds to male hormones, leading to a range of signs and symptoms that can vary widely among individuals. Understanding these symptoms is essential for proper diagnosis and care. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with AIS, which can help us better understand this condition.\nOne of the most common symptoms seen in individuals with AIS is abnormal hair growth patterns. This can manifest as sparse facial hair or a lack of body hair, which may be surprising for those who expect typical male hair growth. In fact, approximately 90% of individuals with this syndrome may experience these hair growth abnormalities.\nAdditionally, AIS can affect the internal reproductive organs. Many individuals may have what is known as male pseudohermaphroditism, where they possess some characteristics of both male and female bodies. This means that while they may have a 46,XY karyotype, which is typically associated with males, their internal reproductive structures may not develop in the usual male pattern. This can lead to complications and challenges in reproductive health.\nFertility can also be impacted by AIS, with about 90% of individuals experiencing decreased fertility. This means that they may face difficulties when trying to conceive children, which can be an emotional and challenging experience.\nAnother symptom that can occur in individuals with AIS is the presence of hernias, which are protrusions of tissue through a weak spot in the abdominal wall. Approximately 50% of patients may experience hernias, which can require medical attention.\nThe frequency of these symptoms can vary significantly among individuals with AIS. For instance, while some symptoms are very common, others may be less frequently observed. The HPO provides estimates based on studies that have examined groups of patients. For example, if a study finds that 25 out of 25 individuals exhibit a particular symptom, that would indicate a 100% occurrence rate for that group. However, these frequencies can change depending on the population being studied, and sometimes there may not be enough data to provide a clear frequency for certain symptoms.\nIn addition to the symptoms mentioned, individuals with AIS may also experience other signs such as gynecomastia (breast tissue development), primary amenorrhea (absence of menstruation), and sparse axillary (underarm) and pubic hair. Understanding these various signs and symptoms is crucial for healthcare providers, as it allows them to offer appropriate medical care and support tailored to the needs of individuals with androgen insensitivity syndrome. By raising awareness and understanding of AIS, we can help ensure that those affected receive the care and support they deserve.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a condition that affects how the body responds to male hormones, leading to a range of signs and symptoms that can vary widely among individuals. Understanding these symptoms is essential for proper diagnosis and care. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with AIS, which can help us better understand this condition. One of the most common symptoms seen in individuals with AIS is abnormal hair growth patterns.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Androgen insensitivity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) is a condition that affects how the body responds to male hormones, leading to a range of signs and symptoms that can vary widely among individuals. Understanding these symptoms is essential for proper diagnosis and care. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with AIS, which can help us better understand this condition. One of the most common symptoms seen in individuals with AIS is abnormal hair growth patterns.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Androgen insensitivity syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
