          "id": "medquad-chunk-88cf303071e067c3",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis ?",
          "content": "What are the signs and symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis? Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is a type of arthritis that mainly affects the spine, but it can also have an impact on other areas of the body. This condition often begins during the teenage years or early adulthood, and it can lead to various symptoms that may vary in severity from person to person. One of the most common symptoms is back pain, which can be accompanied by stiffness. Over time, individuals with AS may find that their ability to move their back becomes more limited as the bones in the spine, known as vertebrae, start to fuse together. Some people may experience mild back pain that comes and goes, while others may suffer from more severe and chronic pain that can significantly affect their daily lives.\nIn very severe cases of AS, the rib cage may become stiff, which can make it challenging to take deep breaths. This can lead to difficulties in breathing deeply, which is an important function for overall health. In addition to the spine, AS can also affect other parts of the body, including the shoulders, hips, knees, and even the small joints in the hands and feet. It may also impact areas where tendons and ligaments attach to bones, leading to additional discomfort and complications.\nWhile AS primarily affects the musculoskeletal system, it can also impact other organs in rare cases. For instance, some individuals may experience inflammation in the eyes, which can cause eye pain and increased sensitivity to light, a condition known as photophobia. Neurological complications can also arise from AS, including difficulties with bladder and bowel control, known as incontinence, and absent reflexes in the ankles due to pressure on the lower part of the spinal cord, a condition referred to as cauda equina syndrome.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that provides a list of signs and symptoms associated with Ankylosing spondylitis. This information can help healthcare professionals and patients understand the condition better. Below is a summary of some common signs and symptoms of AS, along with approximate frequencies based on available data:\n- Abnormal form of the vertebral bodies is seen in about 90% of patients.\n- Abnormality of the oral cavity is reported in 90% of cases.\n- Abnormality of the sacroiliac joint, which connects the spine to the pelvis, is found in 90% of individuals.\n- Arthralgia, or joint pain, occurs in 90% of patients.\n- Arthritis, which is inflammation of the joints, is seen in 90% of cases.\n- Diarrhea may affect 90% of individuals with AS.\n- Enthesitis, which is inflammation where tendons attach to bones, is reported in 90% of patients.\n- Inflammatory abnormalities of the eye are seen in 90% of individuals, which can lead to significant discomfort.\n- Joint swelling is reported in 90% of cases, indicating inflammation in the joints.\n- Spinal rigidity, or stiffness in the spine, is seen in 90% of patients, which can limit mobility.\n- Abnormality of the thorax, or chest area, is found in about 50% of cases.\n- Myalgia, or muscle pain, is reported in 50% of individuals.\n- Respiratory insufficiency, or difficulty breathing, may affect 50% of patients, especially in severe cases.\n- Abdominal pain is reported in 7.5% of cases, which can be uncomfortable and concerning.\n- Abnormal tendon morphology, or changes in tendon structure, is seen in 7.5% of individuals.\n- Other abnormalities, such as issues with temperature regulation, the aortic valve, pericardium, and pleura, are also noted in 7.5% of cases.\n- Additional symptoms may include anorexia (loss of appetite), arrhythmia (irregular heartbeat), autoimmunity (where the body attacks its own tissues), cartilage destruction, hematuria (blood in urine), hemiplegia/hemiparesis (weakness on one side of the body), hyperkeratosis (thickened skin), nephrolithiasis (kidney stones), nephropathy (kidney disease), nephrotic syndrome, osteomyelitis (bone infection), proteinuria (protein in urine), pulmonary fibrosis (lung scarring), pustules (small bumps on the skin), recurrent fractures, recurrent urinary tract infections, renal insufficiency (kidney failure), skin rash, and skin ulcers. Anterior uveitis (inflammation of the eye) and aortic regurgitation (a heart valve issue) may also occur in some patients.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology collects data on how often these symptoms occur, primarily from Orphanet, a European database focused on rare diseases. The frequency of each symptom is usually expressed as a rough estimate of the percentage of patients exhibiting that feature. Sometimes, this information is presented as a fraction, where the numerator indicates how many individuals experienced the symptom, and the denominator represents the total number of individuals studied. For example, a frequency of 25/25 indicates that all individuals in a study of 25 exhibited that symptom. However, these frequencies can vary based on different patient groups. In some instances, information on symptom frequency may not be available, which could suggest that the symptom is either rare or more common. Understanding these signs and symptoms is crucial for early diagnosis and effective management of Ankylosing spondylitis, allowing individuals to seek appropriate medical care and support.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis? Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is a type of arthritis that mainly affects the spine, but it can also have an impact on other areas of the body. This condition often begins during the teenage years or early adulthood, and it can lead to various symptoms that may vary in severity from person to person. One of the most common symptoms is back pain, which can be accompanied by stiffness.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis? Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is a type of arthritis that mainly affects the spine, but it can also have an impact on other areas of the body. This condition often begins during the teenage years or early adulthood, and it can lead to various symptoms that may vary in severity from person to person. One of the most common symptoms is back pain, which can be accompanied by stiffness.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ankylosing spondylitis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
