          "id": "medquad-chunk-6e44b58ba91a4c99",
          "title": "What is (are) Anonychia congenita ?",
          "content": "Anonychia congenita is an exceptionally rare condition that impacts the nails, leading to either the complete absence of fingernails and toenails or their unusual development. This means that individuals with anonychia congenita may not have any nails at all, or their nails may be very different from what is typically seen. Interestingly, people with this condition usually do not experience any problems with their hair, teeth, or bones, which can be a relief for those affected. The signs and symptoms of anonychia congenita can vary significantly from one person to another, even among family members who share the same genetic background. This variability can make it challenging to predict how the condition will manifest in different individuals. As of now, fewer than 20 people with anonychia congenita have been documented around the globe, highlighting its rarity. Researchers believe that this condition is caused by mutations in a specific gene called RSPO4. It is important to note that anonychia congenita is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that for a child to be affected by this condition, both parents must carry the mutated gene, even if they do not show any symptoms themselves. Understanding anonychia congenita is crucial for individuals who may be affected or have family members with this condition, as it can aid in managing expectations and seeking the right medical care and support.\nContext recap: Anonychia congenita is an exceptionally rare condition that impacts the nails, leading to either the complete absence of fingernails and toenails or their unusual development. This means that individuals with anonychia congenita may not have any nails at all, or their nails may be very different from what is typically seen. Interestingly, people with this condition usually do not experience any problems with their hair, teeth, or bones, which can be a relief for those affected. The signs and symptoms of anonychia congenita can vary significantly from one person to another, even among family members who share the same genetic background.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Anonychia congenita ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Anonychia congenita is an exceptionally rare condition that impacts the nails, leading to either the complete absence of fingernails and toenails or their unusual development. This means that individuals with anonychia congenita may not have any nails at all, or their nails may be very different from what is typically seen. Interestingly, people with this condition usually do not experience any problems with their hair, teeth, or bones, which can be a relief for those affected. The signs and symptoms of anonychia congenita can vary significantly from one person to another, even among family members who share the same genetic background.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Anonychia congenita ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Anonychia congenita is an exceptionally rare condition that impacts the nails, leading to either the complete absence of fingernails and toenails or their unusual development. This means that individuals with anonychia congenita may not have any nails at all, or their nails may be very different from what is typically seen. Interestingly, people with this condition usually do not experience any problems with their hair, teeth, or bones, which can be a relief for those affected. The signs and symptoms of anonychia congenita can vary significantly from one person to another, even among family members who share the same genetic background.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Anonychia congenita ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
