          "id": "medquad-chunk-6fe87e84b2307688",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Anophthalmia plus syndrome ?",
          "content": "What are the signs and symptoms of Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome? Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome (APS) is a rare condition that can affect many parts of the body, leading to various malformations. This can include the eyes, ears, nose, face, mouth, brain, and even the spine. Based on the limited number of cases reported in medical literature, it appears that every individual diagnosed with APS has experienced anophthalmia, which is the absence of one or both eyes, and/or microphthalmia, where the eyes are abnormally small.\nResearch suggests that approximately 89% of individuals with this syndrome also have an oral-facial cleft, which can manifest as a cleft lip or a cleft palate. Other common features observed in more than one affected individual include wide-set eyes, known as hypertelorism, low-set ears, and conditions that cause narrowing or blockage of the nasal passages, referred to as choanal stenosis or atresia.\nIn addition to these symptoms, there may be complications involving the spine, abdominal wall, and other body systems. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that provides a detailed list of signs and symptoms associated with Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome. If you are curious about the frequency of these symptoms, the table below outlines how often each symptom is observed in individuals with this condition. For further understanding of any medical terms, you can refer to the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary.\nHere are some of the symptoms of Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome and their approximate occurrence in patients:\n- Aplasia or hypoplasia affecting the eye: 90% of patients\n- Choanal atresia: 50% of patients\n- Cleft palate: 50% of patients\n- Facial cleft: 50% of patients\n- Hypertelorism: 50% of patients\n- Low-set, posteriorly rotated ears: 50% of patients\n- Non-midline cleft lip: 50% of patients\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) gathers important information about how frequently certain signs or symptoms occur in various conditions. Much of this data is sourced from Orphanet, a European database that focuses on rare diseases. The frequency of a symptom is typically expressed as an estimate of the percentage of patients who exhibit that feature. Sometimes, this frequency is represented as a fraction, where the first number indicates how many people had the symptom, and the second number represents the total number of individuals examined in a study. For example, a frequency of 25/25 means that all 25 individuals studied exhibited that symptom.\nIt's crucial to understand that these frequencies can vary based on different studies, and in some cases, there may be no available information on the frequency of a symptom. This could indicate that the symptom is either rare or more common than expected. Understanding these symptoms and their frequencies can help in recognizing and diagnosing Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome, leading to better support and care for those affected by this condition.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome? Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome (APS) is a rare condition that can affect many parts of the body, leading to various malformations. This can include the eyes, ears, nose, face, mouth, brain, and even the spine. Based on the limited number of cases reported in medical literature, it appears that every individual diagnosed with APS has experienced anophthalmia, which is the absence of one or both eyes, and/or microphthalmia, where the eyes are abnormally small.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Anophthalmia plus syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome? Anophthalmia Plus Syndrome (APS) is a rare condition that can affect many parts of the body, leading to various malformations. This can include the eyes, ears, nose, face, mouth, brain, and even the spine. Based on the limited number of cases reported in medical literature, it appears that every individual diagnosed with APS has experienced anophthalmia, which is the absence of one or both eyes, and/or microphthalmia, where the eyes are abnormally small.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Anophthalmia plus syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
