          "id": "medquad-chunk-48a457a6de333cbf",
          "title": "What is (are) Antley Bixler syndrome ?",
          "content": "What is Antley Bixler syndrome? Antley Bixler syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects how the skull and skeleton develop. This means that people with this syndrome may have unique physical features and health challenges that can vary widely from one person to another. Some common signs of Antley Bixler syndrome include craniosynostosis, which is when the bones in the skull fuse together too early, causing the head to have an unusual shape. Other features can include midface hypoplasia, where the middle part of the face is underdeveloped, and frontal bossing, which is when the forehead appears more prominent than usual. Additionally, individuals may have protruding eyes and ears that are low-set or shaped differently than typical ears.\nSome people with this syndrome may also experience choanal atresia, which is a blockage in the nasal passage that can make breathing difficult. Another symptom can be the fusion of adjacent arm bones, known as synostosis, which can limit movement. Joint contractures, where the joints become stiff and difficult to move, are also common. Some individuals may have arachnodactyly, which means their fingers are longer than average, and bowing of the thigh bones, which can affect walking. Urogenital abnormalities can also occur, impacting the urinary tract and reproductive organs.\nThe exact cause of Antley Bixler syndrome is not always known, but some cases are linked to changes, or mutations, in specific genes, such as the FGFR2 gene or the POR gene. There are different forms of this condition, including autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive types, which refer to how the syndrome can be inherited. Treatment for Antley Bixler syndrome is tailored to each individual, focusing on managing the specific symptoms they experience. This personalized approach helps ensure that each person receives the best possible care for their unique needs.\nContext recap: What is Antley Bixler syndrome? Antley Bixler syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects how the skull and skeleton develop. This means that people with this syndrome may have unique physical features and health challenges that can vary widely from one person to another. Some common signs of Antley Bixler syndrome include craniosynostosis, which is when the bones in the skull fuse together too early, causing the head to have an unusual shape.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Antley Bixler syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: What is Antley Bixler syndrome? Antley Bixler syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects how the skull and skeleton develop. This means that people with this syndrome may have unique physical features and health challenges that can vary widely from one person to another. Some common signs of Antley Bixler syndrome include craniosynostosis, which is when the bones in the skull fuse together too early, causing the head to have an unusual shape.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Antley Bixler syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
