          "id": "medquad-chunk-83715018448f8be7",
          "title": "What is (are) Apert syndrome ?",
          "content": "Apert syndrome is a genetic condition that affects how a person's skull and face develop. One of the main features of this syndrome is craniosynostosis, which occurs when the bones in the skull fuse together too early. This can lead to unusual shapes of the head and face, making it different from what we typically see. Another important characteristic of Apert syndrome is syndactyly, where some fingers and/or toes are fused together or webbed, which can affect how a person uses their hands and feet.\nPeople with Apert syndrome may also have unique facial features. For example, they might have wide-set eyes that bulge out a bit, a nose that looks like a beak, and an upper jaw that is not fully developed. This can lead to crowded teeth and other dental issues. Additionally, the eye sockets may be shallow, which can lead to problems with vision.\nSome individuals with this syndrome might have extra fingers or toes, a condition known as polydactyly. Other challenges can include hearing loss and excessive sweating, a condition called hyperhidrosis.\nWhen it comes to thinking and learning, people with Apert syndrome can have a wide range of abilities. Some may have normal cognitive skills, while others might experience mild to moderate intellectual disabilities.\nApert syndrome is caused by changes, or mutations, in a specific gene known as FGFR2. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant way, meaning that if one parent has the mutated gene, there is a chance that their child may also inherit it.\nTo help manage the symptoms and challenges associated with Apert syndrome, individuals often undergo various surgical procedures. These surgeries are customized to meet the specific needs of each person, helping them lead healthier and more fulfilling lives.\nContext recap: Apert syndrome is a genetic condition that affects how a person's skull and face develop. One of the main features of this syndrome is craniosynostosis, which occurs when the bones in the skull fuse together too early. This can lead to unusual shapes of the head and face, making it different from what we typically see. Another important characteristic of Apert syndrome is syndactyly, where some fingers and/or toes are fused together or webbed, which can affect how a person uses their hands and feet.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Apert syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Apert syndrome is a genetic condition that affects how a person's skull and face develop. One of the main features of this syndrome is craniosynostosis, which occurs when the bones in the skull fuse together too early. This can lead to unusual shapes of the head and face, making it different from what we typically see. Another important characteristic of Apert syndrome is syndactyly, where some fingers and/or toes are fused together or webbed, which can affect how a person uses their hands and feet.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Apert syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
