          "id": "medquad-chunk-d7ec561f546b7e0b",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Arachnodactyly - intellectual disability - dysmorphism ?",
          "content": "Arachnodactyly, intellectual disability, and dysmorphism are medical conditions that can show a wide range of signs and symptoms. These conditions are often studied and categorized by researchers to better understand how they affect individuals. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO), which is a valuable resource for information about human diseases, there are several symptoms that are frequently associated with these conditions.\nOne of the most noticeable symptoms is arachnodactyly, which is characterized by long, spider-like fingers. This symptom is observed in approximately 90% of individuals who have been diagnosed with these conditions. Cognitive impairment, which refers to challenges with thinking, learning, and memory, is also reported in about 90% of cases. This means that many individuals may find it difficult to process information or learn new skills.\nIn addition to these primary symptoms, there are other common features that can be seen in around 90% of patients. These include decreased body weight, which may indicate nutritional challenges or other health issues, as well as physical characteristics such as a long face and a narrow face. These features can help healthcare professionals recognize the condition early on.\nOther symptoms that may be present in about half of the individuals diagnosed with these conditions include thin vermilion borders of the lips, which is the area where the lips meet the skin of the face. Trismus, or difficulty opening the mouth, can also occur, making it challenging for individuals to eat or speak comfortably. Additionally, there may be abnormalities related to the immune system and the genitalia, which can affect overall health and development.\nUnderstanding these symptoms is crucial for healthcare providers, as it can assist in identifying the condition and managing it effectively. Early diagnosis and intervention can lead to better outcomes for individuals affected by arachnodactyly, intellectual disability, and dysmorphism. It is important for families and caregivers to be aware of these signs so they can seek appropriate medical advice and support when needed.\nThe information about the frequency of these symptoms comes from various studies and databases, including Orphanet, which is a European database focused on rare diseases. The frequency of a symptom is typically expressed as a percentage, indicating how many individuals in a study exhibited that particular symptom. For instance, if a study reports that 25 out of 25 individuals had a specific symptom, it means that every person examined showed that feature. However, it is important to note that these frequencies can vary depending on the population being studied. In some cases, there may not be enough information available to determine how common or rare a symptom is, which can make understanding these conditions more complex.\nIn summary, recognizing the signs and symptoms associated with arachnodactyly, intellectual disability, and dysmorphism is essential for effective diagnosis and management. By being informed about these conditions, individuals and their families can work closely with healthcare professionals to ensure they receive the best possible care and support.\nContext recap: Arachnodactyly, intellectual disability, and dysmorphism are medical conditions that can show a wide range of signs and symptoms. These conditions are often studied and categorized by researchers to better understand how they affect individuals. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO), which is a valuable resource for information about human diseases, there are several symptoms that are frequently associated with these conditions. One of the most noticeable symptoms is arachnodactyly, which is characterized by long, spider-like fingers.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Arachnodactyly - intellectual disability - dysmorphism ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Arachnodactyly, intellectual disability, and dysmorphism are medical conditions that can show a wide range of signs and symptoms. These conditions are often studied and categorized by researchers to better understand how they affect individuals. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO), which is a valuable resource for information about human diseases, there are several symptoms that are frequently associated with these conditions. One of the most noticeable symptoms is arachnodactyly, which is characterized by long, spider-like fingers.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Arachnodactyly - intellectual disability - dysmorphism ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
