          "id": "medquad-chunk-f5610a54701a51bd",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 ?",
          "content": "Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 is a rare condition that affects how a person moves and coordinates their body. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this condition is important for diagnosis and management. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with this condition, including how often they occur in individuals diagnosed with it. If you come across any medical terms that you find confusing, you can look them up in the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary, which provides clear definitions to help you understand better.\nSome of the most common symptoms of Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 include:\n- **Impaired Distal Tactile Sensation**: This means that individuals may have difficulty feeling sensations in their hands and feet. Approximately 57% of patients experience this symptom.\n- **Tremor**: Many individuals may experience shaking movements, particularly in their hands. This is also seen in about 57% of patients.\n- **Strabismus**: This is a condition where the eyes do not properly align with each other, affecting vision. It occurs in about 30% of individuals with this condition.\n- **Conjunctival Telangiectasia**: This refers to small, dilated blood vessels on the surface of the eye, seen in about 5% of patients.\n- **Areflexia**: This is the absence of reflexes, which can be a significant indicator of neurological issues. It is noted in all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Cerebellar Atrophy**: This involves the shrinking of the cerebellum, which is crucial for coordination and balance. This symptom is observed in all patients examined (8 out of 8).\n- **Distal Amyotrophy**: This refers to muscle wasting in the hands and feet, affecting 10 out of 10 patients.\n- **Distal Muscle Weakness**: Weakness in the muscles farthest from the center of the body is also common, affecting all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Dysarthria**: This is a speech disorder that affects the clarity of speech, seen in all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Dysphagia**: Difficulty swallowing is another symptom that affects all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Elevated Alpha-Fetoprotein**: This is a blood test finding that can indicate various conditions, noted in all patients examined (6 out of 6).\n- **Gait Ataxia**: This refers to unsteady walking, which is seen in all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Impaired Proprioception**: This is the inability to sense the position of one’s body parts, affecting all patients examined (10 out of 10).\n- **Peripheral Axonal Neuropathy**: This condition affects the peripheral nerves and is observed in 8 out of 8 patients.\n- **Nystagmus**: This is an involuntary eye movement that can affect vision, seen in 8 out of 10 patients.\n- **Pes Cavus**: This is a condition where the foot has an excessively high arch, affecting 12 out of 18 patients.\n- **Oculomotor Apraxia**: This refers to difficulty with eye movements, noted in 10 out of 18 patients.\n- **Scoliosis**: This is a curvature of the spine, affecting 7 out of 18 patients.\n- **Dystonia**: This involves involuntary muscle contractions, seen in 5 out of 18 patients.\n- **Head Tremor**: This is shaking of the head, noted in 5 out of 19 patients.\n- **Chorea**: This refers to irregular, unintentional movements, affecting 4 out of 18 patients.\n- **Hyporeflexia**: This is reduced reflexes, noted in 4 out of 18 patients.\n- **Abnormal Pyramidal Signs**: These signs indicate issues with the brain's motor pathways.\n- **Autosomal Recessive Inheritance**: This means that the condition is passed down through families in a specific genetic pattern.\n- **Decreased Motor Nerve Conduction Velocity**: This indicates slower nerve signals, which can affect movement.\n- **Elevated Serum Creatine Phosphokinase**: This is a blood test result that can indicate muscle damage.\n- **Gaze-Evoked Nystagmus**: This is a specific type of eye movement disorder.\n- **Impaired Distal Vibration Sensation**: This refers to difficulty feeling vibrations in the hands and feet.\n- **Increased Antibody Level in Blood**: This can indicate an immune response.\n- **Limb Ataxia**: This refers to uncoordinated movements in the limbs.\n- **Polyneuropathy**: This is a condition affecting multiple peripheral nerves.\n- **Pontocerebellar Atrophy**: This is a specific type of brain atrophy affecting coordination.\n- **Progressive Gait Ataxia**: This means that the unsteady walking may worsen over time.\n- **Saccadic Smooth Pursuit**: This refers to difficulty in smoothly following moving objects with the eyes.\n- **Variable Expressivity**: This means that symptoms can vary widely among individuals with the same condition.\nThe information about how often these symptoms occur is usually based on research studies, and it can vary from one study to another. For example, if a study finds that 57% of participants have a specific symptom, it suggests that this symptom is relatively common among those with Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2. However, some symptoms might not have enough data available, which means they could be either rare or more common than expected. Understanding these symptoms can help in recognizing the condition and seeking appropriate medical advice.\nContext recap: Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 is a rare condition that affects how a person moves and coordinates their body. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this condition is important for diagnosis and management. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with this condition, including how often they occur in individuals diagnosed with it. If you come across any medical terms that you find confusing, you can look them up in the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary, which provides clear definitions to help you understand better.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 is a rare condition that affects how a person moves and coordinates their body. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this condition is important for diagnosis and management. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered valuable information about the symptoms associated with this condition, including how often they occur in individuals diagnosed with it. If you come across any medical terms that you find confusing, you can look them up in the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary, which provides clear definitions to help you understand better.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ataxia with Oculomotor Apraxia Type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
