          "id": "medquad-chunk-a28388cbf500a0be",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1 ?",
          "content": "What are the signs and symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1? Atelosteogenesis type 1 is a rare genetic condition that affects the development of bones and other parts of the body. Individuals with this condition may experience a variety of symptoms that can impact their overall health and physical appearance. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that provides a comprehensive list of these symptoms, along with information on how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with Atelosteogenesis type 1. If you come across any medical terms that you find confusing, you can refer to the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary, which offers clear definitions to help you understand better.\nSome of the most common symptoms associated with Atelosteogenesis type 1 include:\n- **Abnormalities in bone structure**: This can manifest as short limbs, which means that the arms and legs may not grow to typical lengths.\n- **Cleft palate**: This is a condition where there is an opening in the roof of the mouth, which can affect eating and speaking.\n- **Clubbing**: This refers to the enlargement of the fingertips and toes, which can occur due to various health issues.\n- **Club-shaped proximal femur**: This means that the upper part of the thigh bone (femur) is shaped differently than usual.\n- **Elbow dislocation**: This occurs when the bones of the elbow joint are not aligned properly.\n- **Hypoplasia of midface**: This is a condition where the middle part of the face does not develop fully, which can affect facial appearance.\n- **Short neck and short nose**: These features can also be observed in individuals with this condition.\nThe frequency of these symptoms can vary significantly among individuals with Atelosteogenesis type 1. Researchers often estimate how common a symptom is based on studies conducted with groups of patients. For instance, if a study finds that 25 out of 25 participants exhibited a specific symptom, it suggests that this symptom is very common among those with the condition. However, if a symptom has not been studied extensively, there may not be enough data to determine how frequently it occurs, which means it could be either rare or more common than expected.\nUnderstanding the signs and symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1 is crucial for early diagnosis and management of the condition. It helps healthcare providers offer better care and support to individuals affected by this rare disease. If you are interested in learning more about any specific symptoms or their implications, feel free to explore additional resources or consult with a medical professional who specializes in rare diseases. They can provide you with more detailed information and guidance tailored to your needs.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1? Atelosteogenesis type 1 is a rare genetic condition that affects the development of bones and other parts of the body. Individuals with this condition may experience a variety of symptoms that can impact their overall health and physical appearance. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that provides a comprehensive list of these symptoms, along with information on how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with Atelosteogenesis type 1.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1? Atelosteogenesis type 1 is a rare genetic condition that affects the development of bones and other parts of the body. Individuals with this condition may experience a variety of symptoms that can impact their overall health and physical appearance. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) is a valuable resource that provides a comprehensive list of these symptoms, along with information on how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with Atelosteogenesis type 1.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Atelosteogenesis type 1 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
