          "id": "medquad-chunk-c74d2e5b53c58030",
          "title": "What is (are) Atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome ?",
          "content": "Atypical hemolytic-uremic syndrome, commonly referred to as aHUS, is a rare and serious medical condition that affects how blood clots form in small blood vessels, particularly in the kidneys. When these clots form abnormally, they can block or restrict blood flow, which can lead to significant health problems. Some of the serious issues that can arise from aHUS include hemolytic anemia, which is a condition where red blood cells are destroyed faster than they can be made, and kidney failure, where the kidneys can no longer filter waste from the blood effectively.\nThis syndrome can affect individuals of any age, from infants to older adults. The causes of aHUS are often a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Genetic factors involve specific genes that play a crucial role in regulating the complement system, which is a part of the immune system that helps the body fight infections and clear damaged cells. When these genes are mutated or not functioning properly, it can lead to the development of aHUS.\nOn the other hand, environmental factors can also contribute to the onset of aHUS. These factors may include certain medications, such as anticancer drugs, chronic diseases like systemic sclerosis or malignant hypertension, infections caused by viruses or bacteria, certain types of cancers, organ transplants, and even pregnancy.\nInterestingly, most cases of aHUS are sporadic, meaning they occur randomly without a clear family history. However, about 20% of cases have been reported to run in families, indicating a genetic predisposition. When aHUS is familial, it can be inherited in different ways, either through an autosomal dominant pattern, where only one copy of the mutated gene is needed to cause the disorder, or an autosomal recessive pattern, where two copies of the mutated gene are required.\nIt is important to note that atypical hemolytic-uremic syndrome is different from a more common condition known as typical hemolytic-uremic syndrome. While both conditions affect the kidneys and blood clotting, they have different underlying causes and present with different signs and symptoms. Understanding these differences is crucial for proper diagnosis and treatment.\nIn summary, aHUS is a complex condition that requires careful medical attention and management. If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms related to this syndrome, it is essential to seek medical advice for appropriate evaluation and care.\nContext recap: Atypical hemolytic-uremic syndrome, commonly referred to as aHUS, is a rare and serious medical condition that affects how blood clots form in small blood vessels, particularly in the kidneys. When these clots form abnormally, they can block or restrict blood flow, which can lead to significant health problems. Some of the serious issues that can arise from aHUS include hemolytic anemia, which is a condition where red blood cells are destroyed faster than they can be made, and kidney failure, where the kidneys can no longer filter waste from the blood effectively. This syndrome can affect individuals of any age, from infants to older adults.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Atypical hemolytic-uremic syndrome, commonly referred to as aHUS, is a rare and serious medical condition that affects how blood clots form in small blood vessels, particularly in the kidneys. When these clots form abnormally, they can block or restrict blood flow, which can lead to significant health problems. Some of the serious issues that can arise from aHUS include hemolytic anemia, which is a condition where red blood cells are destroyed faster than they can be made, and kidney failure, where the kidneys can no longer filter waste from the blood effectively. This syndrome can affect individuals of any age, from infants to older adults.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
