          "id": "medquad-chunk-d4db0af8fe374f53",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome ?",
          "content": "Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that can lead to a variety of noticeable signs and symptoms in those affected. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for diagnosis and management. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology, which is a comprehensive resource that categorizes human diseases based on their symptoms, the following are some of the most common features associated with Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in individuals with this condition:\n1. **Non-midline cleft lip**: This is a type of cleft lip that occurs on one side of the lip rather than in the middle. It is observed in approximately 90% of patients with this syndrome, making it one of the most prevalent symptoms.\n2. **Abnormality of retinal pigmentation**: This refers to unusual coloring in the retina, which is the light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye. About 50% of individuals with Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome may experience this symptom, which can affect vision.\n3. **Visual impairment**: Many patients, around 50%, may also face challenges with their vision, which can range from mild to severe.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology collects and organizes data about how often these signs and symptoms occur in various conditions. Much of this information is sourced from Orphanet, a specialized European database that focuses on rare diseases. The frequency of each symptom is typically expressed as a percentage or as a fraction. For example, if a symptom is noted as 25/25, this indicates that all 25 individuals studied exhibited that particular symptom. This method helps researchers and healthcare providers understand how common or rare a symptom is within a specific population.\nIt's important to note that these frequencies can vary based on different studies and the populations being examined. In some cases, there may not be enough data available to determine how frequently a symptom occurs. When this happens, it could mean that the symptom is either very rare or perhaps more common than expected. Understanding these signs and symptoms is essential for healthcare professionals when diagnosing and treating individuals with Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome, as it helps them provide the best possible care and support to those affected by this rare condition.\nContext recap: Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that can lead to a variety of noticeable signs and symptoms in those affected. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for diagnosis and management. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology, which is a comprehensive resource that categorizes human diseases based on their symptoms, the following are some of the most common features associated with Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in individuals with this condition:\n1. **Non-midline cleft lip**: This is a type of cleft lip that occurs on one side of the lip rather than in the middle.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that can lead to a variety of noticeable signs and symptoms in those affected. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for diagnosis and management. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology, which is a comprehensive resource that categorizes human diseases based on their symptoms, the following are some of the most common features associated with Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in individuals with this condition:\n1. **Non-midline cleft lip**: This is a type of cleft lip that occurs on one side of the lip rather than in the middle.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Ausems Wittebol-Post Hennekam syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
