          "id": "medquad-chunk-fe3f5a59218f39dc",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C ?",
          "content": "Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C is a genetic disorder that primarily impacts the peripheral nerves, which are responsible for transmitting signals between the brain, spinal cord, and the rest of the body. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent carries the gene for this disorder, there is a 50% chance that their child will also inherit it. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this disease is crucial for early diagnosis and management.\nAccording to the Human Phenotype Ontology, a comprehensive resource that categorizes various medical conditions, several key symptoms are associated with Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C. One of the most noticeable symptoms is an abnormality of the foot, which can present in different forms, such as high arches or flat feet. These foot abnormalities can lead to difficulties in walking and may require special footwear or orthotics to help with mobility.\nAnother significant symptom is axonal regeneration, which refers to the ability of nerve fibers to repair themselves after injury. While this is a positive aspect, it can also indicate that the nerves are under stress or damage. Additionally, distal amyotrophy is commonly observed in individuals with this condition. This term describes the wasting away of muscle tissue in the extremities, particularly in the hands and feet, leading to weakness and reduced muscle mass.\nPatients may also experience distal muscle weakness, which affects the strength of muscles in the arms and legs, making everyday tasks more challenging. Alongside muscle weakness, distal sensory impairment is often reported, meaning that individuals may have reduced sensitivity to touch, pain, or temperature in their extremities. This can lead to difficulties in feeling injuries or changes in temperature, increasing the risk of accidents.\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology gathers data on how frequently these symptoms occur in individuals with Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C. This information is derived from various studies, including those conducted by Orphanet, a European database dedicated to rare diseases. The frequency of a symptom is typically expressed as an estimate of the percentage of patients who exhibit that particular feature. For instance, if a study finds that a symptom is present in 25 out of 25 patients, it suggests that all individuals in that study experienced that symptom. However, it is important to note that these frequencies can vary based on different studies and populations, and sometimes, there may be no available data on the frequency of certain symptoms. In such cases, it could indicate that the symptom is either rare or not commonly reported.\nIn summary, understanding the symptoms of Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C is essential for those affected and their families. Early recognition of these signs can lead to better management strategies and improved quality of life for individuals living with this condition. If you or someone you know is experiencing these symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation and support.\nContext recap: Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C is a genetic disorder that primarily impacts the peripheral nerves, which are responsible for transmitting signals between the brain, spinal cord, and the rest of the body. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent carries the gene for this disorder, there is a 50% chance that their child will also inherit it. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this disease is crucial for early diagnosis and management. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology, a comprehensive resource that categorizes various medical conditions, several key symptoms are associated with Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C.\nContext recap: Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C is a genetic disorder that primarily impacts the peripheral nerves, which are responsible for transmitting signals between the brain, spinal cord, and the rest of the body. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent carries the gene for this disorder, there is a 50% chance that their child will also inherit it. Understanding the signs and symptoms of this disease is crucial for early diagnosis and management. According to the Human Phenotype Ontology, a comprehensive resource that categorizes various medical conditions, several key symptoms are associated with Autosomal dominant intermediate Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type C.",
