          "id": "medquad-chunk-ddb65d795329b568",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Autosomal dominant optic atrophy plus syndrome ?",
          "content": "What are the signs and symptoms of Autosomal Dominant Optic Atrophy Plus Syndrome? This condition is associated with a variety of symptoms that can affect individuals differently. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered important information about these symptoms, which can help us understand how this syndrome impacts those who have it. Below, we will explore some of the common signs and symptoms associated with this syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with this condition. If you come across any medical terms that are unfamiliar, you can look them up in the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary for better understanding.\nSome of the most frequently reported symptoms include:\n1. **Impaired Pain Sensation**: This symptom is observed in about 90% of individuals with this syndrome. It means that people may not feel pain as they normally would, which can lead to injuries or other complications.\n2. **Optic Atrophy**: Also seen in approximately 90% of patients, optic atrophy refers to the damage or loss of nerve fibers in the optic nerve, which can lead to vision problems.\n3. **Sensorineural Hearing Impairment**: This is another common symptom, affecting around 90% of individuals. It involves issues with hearing that arise from problems in the inner ear or the auditory nerve.\n4. **Visual Impairment**: About 50% of individuals may experience some form of visual impairment, which can range from mild to severe.\n5. **Abnormality of Color Vision**: This symptom is noted in about 50% of patients, indicating that they may have difficulty distinguishing between certain colors.\n6. **Abnormality of Visual Evoked Potentials**: This occurs in about 7.5% of individuals and relates to the brain's response to visual stimuli.\n7. **Decreased Nerve Conduction Velocity**: Also seen in about 7.5% of patients, this refers to slower than normal transmission of electrical signals in the nerves.\n8. **Strabismus**: This is a condition where the eyes do not properly align with each other, affecting about 7.5% of individuals.\n9. **Ataxia**: This symptom, affecting around 5% of patients, involves a lack of muscle control or coordination.\nOther symptoms that may occur, but are less common, include:\n- Abnormal amplitude of pattern reversal visual evoked potentials\n- Abnormal auditory evoked potentials\n- Central scotoma (a blind spot in the center of vision)\n- Centrocecal scotoma (a type of visual field defect)\n- Horizontal nystagmus (involuntary eye movement)\n- Increased variability in muscle fiber diameter\n- Myopathy (muscle weakness)\n- Ophthalmoplegia (weakness of the eye muscles)\n- Peripheral neuropathy (nerve damage outside the brain and spinal cord)\n- Phenotypic variability (differences in symptoms among individuals)\n- Progressive sensorineural hearing impairment\n- Ptosis (drooping of the upper eyelid)\n- Red-green dyschromatopsia (difficulty distinguishing red and green colors)\n- Reduced visual acuity (clarity of vision)\n- Tritanomaly (a type of color vision deficiency)\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology provides valuable insights into how often these signs and symptoms occur in individuals with Autosomal Dominant Optic Atrophy Plus Syndrome. Much of this information is sourced from Orphanet, a European database dedicated to rare diseases. The frequency of a symptom is often expressed as a percentage, indicating how many individuals in a study exhibited that symptom. For example, if a study reports that 25 out of 25 individuals had a specific symptom, it would be noted as 100%. However, these frequencies can vary based on different studies and the populations examined. In some cases, there may be no available information about the frequency of certain symptoms, which could suggest that they are either rare or more common than expected. Understanding these symptoms is crucial for diagnosis and management of the condition, and ongoing research continues to shed light on the complexities of Autosomal Dominant Optic Atrophy Plus Syndrome.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Autosomal Dominant Optic Atrophy Plus Syndrome? This condition is associated with a variety of symptoms that can affect individuals differently. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered important information about these symptoms, which can help us understand how this syndrome impacts those who have it. Below, we will explore some of the common signs and symptoms associated with this syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with this condition.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Autosomal dominant optic atrophy plus syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: What are the signs and symptoms of Autosomal Dominant Optic Atrophy Plus Syndrome? This condition is associated with a variety of symptoms that can affect individuals differently. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered important information about these symptoms, which can help us understand how this syndrome impacts those who have it. Below, we will explore some of the common signs and symptoms associated with this syndrome, along with estimates of how frequently they occur in people diagnosed with this condition.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Autosomal dominant optic atrophy plus syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
          "kind": "concept"
