          "id": "medquad-chunk-f10f766c0198df85",
          "title": "What is (are) Autosomal recessive hyper IgE syndrome ?",
          "content": "Autosomal recessive hyper IgE syndrome (AR-HIES) is a very rare condition that affects the immune system, which is the body's defense against infections. This syndrome is classified as a primary immunodeficiency, meaning that it is caused by genetic factors that impair the immune system's ability to function properly. One of the key features of AR-HIES is the presence of extremely high levels of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood. IgE is a type of antibody that plays a crucial role in allergic reactions and responses to parasites. In individuals with AR-HIES, the elevated IgE levels can lead to various health issues, including recurrent skin infections, particularly staphylococcal skin abscesses, and frequent episodes of pneumonia, which is an infection of the lungs.\nAlthough there is a more common form of hyper IgE syndrome known as autosomal dominant hyper IgE syndrome (AD-HIES), AR-HIES is much rarer, with only about 130 families reported to be affected worldwide. This rarity highlights the uniqueness of AR-HIES in the landscape of immunodeficiency disorders.\nIn addition to high IgE levels, AR-HIES is characterized by a significant increase in eosinophils, which are a type of white blood cell involved in the body's response to allergens and infections. This increase in eosinophils can lead to complications, including a higher susceptibility to viral infections such as Herpes simplex and Molluscum contagiosum.\nAnother important aspect of AR-HIES is its impact on the central nervous system, which can lead to neurological issues. Individuals with this syndrome may also experience defects in T-cells, a type of white blood cell that is essential for the immune response. Unfortunately, AR-HIES is associated with a higher mortality rate compared to its dominant counterpart.\nUnlike AD-HIES, individuals with AR-HIES do not exhibit certain physical features, such as specific dental, skeletal, connective tissue, or facial characteristics. This distinction is important for understanding the differences between the two forms of hyper IgE syndrome.\nAR-HIES is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that for a child to be affected by the condition, both parents must carry and pass on the mutated gene. The genetic basis of AR-HIES is linked to mutations in the DOCK8 gene, which plays a critical role in the immune system's function. Understanding these genetic factors is essential for diagnosis and potential future treatments for those affected by this rare syndrome.\nContext recap: Autosomal recessive hyper IgE syndrome (AR-HIES) is a very rare condition that affects the immune system, which is the body's defense against infections. This syndrome is classified as a primary immunodeficiency, meaning that it is caused by genetic factors that impair the immune system's ability to function properly. One of the key features of AR-HIES is the presence of extremely high levels of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood. IgE is a type of antibody that plays a crucial role in allergic reactions and responses to parasites.\nContext recap: Autosomal recessive hyper IgE syndrome (AR-HIES) is a very rare condition that affects the immune system, which is the body's defense against infections. This syndrome is classified as a primary immunodeficiency, meaning that it is caused by genetic factors that impair the immune system's ability to function properly. One of the key features of AR-HIES is the presence of extremely high levels of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood. IgE is a type of antibody that plays a crucial role in allergic reactions and responses to parasites.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Autosomal recessive hyper IgE syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
