          "id": "medquad-chunk-78d96e0f13b9054f",
          "title": "What is (are) Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome type 2 ?",
          "content": "Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome is a group of eye disorders that affect how the eyes develop. This condition can lead to various eye symptoms, including defects in the cornea, which is the clear covering at the front of the eye, and defects in the iris, which is the colored part of the eye. Individuals with Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome may experience an off-center pupil, known as corectopia, or they may have extra holes in their eyes that can resemble multiple pupils, a condition called polycoria. It's important to note that about 50% of individuals with this syndrome may develop glaucoma, a serious eye condition that increases pressure inside the eye. This elevated pressure can lead to vision loss or even blindness if not managed properly. For a better understanding of the eye's structure, you can click here to view a diagram of the eye.\nWhile Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome primarily affects the eyes, it can also be associated with symptoms that impact other parts of the body. Many individuals with this syndrome exhibit distinctive facial features. Additionally, dental issues are common, with some people having unusually small teeth, a condition known as microdontia, or having fewer teeth than normal, referred to as oligodontia. In some cases, individuals may have extra folds of skin around their belly button, heart defects, or other rare birth defects.\nThere are three recognized types of Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome, each with a different genetic cause. Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome type 1 is caused by mutations in the PITX2 gene, while type 3 is linked to mutations in the FOXC1 gene. The genetic cause of Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome type 2 is currently unknown, but it is believed to be located on chromosome 13. This syndrome follows an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance, meaning that only one copy of the mutated gene from an affected parent can cause the condition in their offspring. Understanding these genetic factors is crucial for diagnosis and management of the syndrome, as well as for providing support to affected individuals and their families.\nContext recap: Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome is a group of eye disorders that affect how the eyes develop. This condition can lead to various eye symptoms, including defects in the cornea, which is the clear covering at the front of the eye, and defects in the iris, which is the colored part of the eye. Individuals with Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome may experience an off-center pupil, known as corectopia, or they may have extra holes in their eyes that can resemble multiple pupils, a condition called polycoria. It's important to note that about 50% of individuals with this syndrome may develop glaucoma, a serious eye condition that increases pressure inside the eye.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome is a group of eye disorders that affect how the eyes develop. This condition can lead to various eye symptoms, including defects in the cornea, which is the clear covering at the front of the eye, and defects in the iris, which is the colored part of the eye. Individuals with Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome may experience an off-center pupil, known as corectopia, or they may have extra holes in their eyes that can resemble multiple pupils, a condition called polycoria. It's important to note that about 50% of individuals with this syndrome may develop glaucoma, a serious eye condition that increases pressure inside the eye.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Axenfeld-Rieger syndrome type 2 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
