          "title": "What are the symptoms of Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 ?",
          "content": "Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 is a rare genetic disorder that can affect many parts of the body. Recognizing the signs and symptoms of this syndrome is very important for early diagnosis and effective treatment. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered a list of symptoms associated with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8, which can help us understand how this condition appears in different individuals. Below is a detailed summary of the symptoms and their approximate frequency in patients. If you come across any medical terms that you are not familiar with, you can refer to the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary for definitions.\n### Signs and Symptoms of Bardet-Biedl Syndrome 8\n1. **Abnormality of the kidney** - This symptom is seen in about 95% of patients, meaning that almost all individuals with this syndrome may have some form of kidney issue.\n2. **Micropenis** - This condition affects around 88% of individuals with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8, indicating that it is quite common among those diagnosed.\n3. **Myopia (nearsightedness)** - This visual impairment is observed in approximately 75% of patients, which means that many individuals may struggle to see distant objects clearly.\n4. **Astigmatism** - Found in about 63% of those affected, astigmatism can cause blurred vision due to an irregular shape of the eye.\n5. **Cataract** - This eye condition occurs in roughly 30% of patients, leading to clouding of the lens and affecting vision.\n6. **Glaucoma** - Affects about 22% of individuals, glaucoma can lead to increased pressure in the eye and potential vision loss if not treated.\n7. **Rod-cone dystrophy** - Seen in around 8% of patients, this condition impacts vision by affecting the light-sensitive cells in the retina.\n8. **Abnormality of the ovary** - Observed in about 7.5% of females, this can lead to various reproductive health issues.\n9. **Hearing impairment** - Affects roughly 7.5% of individuals, indicating that some may experience difficulties with hearing.\n10. **Macrocephaly (larger than normal head size)** - Seen in about 7.5% of patients, this can be a noticeable physical characteristic.\n11. **Vaginal atresia** - This condition affects approximately 7.5% of females, where the vaginal canal is underdeveloped or absent.\n12. **Aganglionic megacolon** - Observed in about 5% of patients, this condition involves a blockage in the colon due to missing nerve cells.\nIn addition to these symptoms, individuals with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 may also experience other issues such as asthma, ataxia (problems with coordination), and various skeletal abnormalities. The frequency of these symptoms can vary based on different studies, and sometimes specific information may not be available. This means that while some symptoms are common, others may be rare. Understanding these symptoms is crucial as it can help healthcare providers offer better care and support for individuals living with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8. By being aware of these signs, families and healthcare professionals can work together to ensure that those affected receive the appropriate medical attention and resources they need to manage their condition effectively.\nContext recap: Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 is a rare genetic disorder that can affect many parts of the body. Recognizing the signs and symptoms of this syndrome is very important for early diagnosis and effective treatment. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered a list of symptoms associated with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8, which can help us understand how this condition appears in different individuals. Below is a detailed summary of the symptoms and their approximate frequency in patients.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 is a rare genetic disorder that can affect many parts of the body. Recognizing the signs and symptoms of this syndrome is very important for early diagnosis and effective treatment. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) has gathered a list of symptoms associated with Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8, which can help us understand how this condition appears in different individuals. Below is a detailed summary of the symptoms and their approximate frequency in patients.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Bardet-Biedl syndrome 8 ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
