          "id": "medquad-chunk-d603e7b41ca0260d",
          "title": "What is (are) Basilar migraine ?",
          "content": "Basilar migraine is a unique type of migraine headache that often presents with a warning sign known as an aura. This type of migraine is characterized by pain that typically occurs on both sides of the back of the head. An aura is a collection of symptoms that serve as an alert that a migraine is about to occur. These symptoms can include feelings of dizziness or vertigo, which is a sensation of spinning, slurred speech, difficulty with coordination (known as ataxia), ringing in the ears (referred to as tinnitus), changes in vision, and problems with balance.\nWhile basilar migraines can affect individuals of all ages, they are most commonly observed in adolescent girls. The exact reasons why basilar migraines occur are not fully understood, but they are believed to be complex conditions influenced by a combination of genetic factors, lifestyle choices, and environmental influences. In rare instances, changes in specific genes, such as the ATP1A2 gene or the CACNA1A gene, may increase the likelihood of experiencing basilar migraines. These genetic factors can interact with other elements in a person's life, making the condition more likely to occur.\nWhen someone experiences an episode of a basilar migraine, healthcare providers typically recommend treatments that include nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) to help reduce pain and antiemetic medications to alleviate nausea. These treatments aim to make the person feel more comfortable during an episode. It is important for individuals who experience these migraines to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop a personalized treatment plan that addresses their specific symptoms and needs. Understanding the triggers and symptoms of basilar migraines can empower individuals to manage their condition more effectively and improve their quality of life.\nIn summary, basilar migraines are a specific type of migraine headache that can significantly impact those who experience them. By recognizing the symptoms and seeking appropriate treatment, individuals can take steps to manage their migraines and reduce their frequency and severity. Education about this condition is crucial for both patients and healthcare providers to ensure effective management and support.\nContext recap: Basilar migraine is a unique type of migraine headache that often presents with a warning sign known as an aura. This type of migraine is characterized by pain that typically occurs on both sides of the back of the head. An aura is a collection of symptoms that serve as an alert that a migraine is about to occur. These symptoms can include feelings of dizziness or vertigo, which is a sensation of spinning, slurred speech, difficulty with coordination (known as ataxia), ringing in the ears (referred to as tinnitus), changes in vision, and problems with balance.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Basilar migraine ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Basilar migraine is a unique type of migraine headache that often presents with a warning sign known as an aura. This type of migraine is characterized by pain that typically occurs on both sides of the back of the head. An aura is a collection of symptoms that serve as an alert that a migraine is about to occur. These symptoms can include feelings of dizziness or vertigo, which is a sensation of spinning, slurred speech, difficulty with coordination (known as ataxia), ringing in the ears (referred to as tinnitus), changes in vision, and problems with balance.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Basilar migraine ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
