          "id": "medquad-chunk-7763cda50d5f0ed8",
          "title": "What is (are) Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome ?",
          "content": "What is Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome? Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is a rare genetic condition that primarily affects the skin and the bones of the skull. Individuals with this syndrome often exhibit unique skin features. One of the main characteristics is cutis gyrata, which causes the skin to appear wrinkled and furrowed, resembling the surface of a brain. Another skin condition associated with this syndrome is acanthosis nigricans, which leads to the development of dark, velvety patches on various parts of the body, particularly in areas like the neck and armpits.\nIn addition to these skin changes, Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome also involves a condition known as craniosynostosis. This occurs when certain bones in the skull fuse together too early, which can restrict the normal growth of the skull. As a result, this premature fusion can lead to an unusual shape of the head and face, which may require medical attention to manage.\nThe underlying cause of Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is mutations in a specific gene called FGFR2. This gene plays a crucial role in the development of various tissues in the body, including skin and bone. The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that only one copy of the mutated gene from either parent can lead to the condition. However, it is important to note that in all documented cases, the mutations have occurred as new changes in the gene, meaning that individuals affected by this syndrome often do not have a family history of the disorder. This highlights the importance of genetic counseling for families who may be affected by rare genetic conditions like Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome.\nContext recap: What is Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome? Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is a rare genetic condition that primarily affects the skin and the bones of the skull. Individuals with this syndrome often exhibit unique skin features. One of the main characteristics is cutis gyrata, which causes the skin to appear wrinkled and furrowed, resembling the surface of a brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What is Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome? Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is a rare genetic condition that primarily affects the skin and the bones of the skull. Individuals with this syndrome often exhibit unique skin features. One of the main characteristics is cutis gyrata, which causes the skin to appear wrinkled and furrowed, resembling the surface of a brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What is Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome? Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is a rare genetic condition that primarily affects the skin and the bones of the skull. Individuals with this syndrome often exhibit unique skin features. One of the main characteristics is cutis gyrata, which causes the skin to appear wrinkled and furrowed, resembling the surface of a brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nGuided check: Ask yourself, \"What is the claim?\", \"Which evidence is strongest?\", and \"What would change my conclusion?\" Use the terms syndrome, cutis, gyrata, beare-stevenson, skin, rare, condition, goal while answering to reinforce vocabulary and precision.",
