          "id": "medquad-chunk-29f3d350fc87cf10",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Behcet's disease ?",
          "content": "Behcet's disease is a complex condition that can affect many parts of the body, leading to a wide range of symptoms. One of the most common signs of this disease is the appearance of painful ulcers in the mouth, which can look similar to canker sores. These ulcers can also occur in the genital area, causing discomfort. Another significant symptom is inflammation of the eyes, known as uveitis, which can lead to vision problems if not treated properly. In addition to these symptoms, individuals with Behcet's disease may experience various skin issues, such as rashes or lesions. The disease can also cause arthritis, leading to joint pain and swelling. Inflammation of the bowel is another possible complication, which can result in abdominal pain and digestive issues. Meningitis, which is the inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord, can also occur, leading to serious health concerns. Behcet's disease is classified as a multi-system disorder, meaning it can impact multiple organs and systems throughout the body. This can lead to more severe complications, including memory loss, difficulties with speech, and problems with balance and movement. In extreme cases, the disease can result in blindness, strokes, swelling of the spinal cord, and serious gastrointestinal issues. The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) provides a comprehensive list of signs and symptoms associated with Behcet's disease, along with estimates of how frequently these symptoms occur in individuals diagnosed with the condition. For those interested in learning more about specific medical terms, the MedlinePlus Medical Dictionary is a helpful resource. Here are some of the common signs and symptoms of Behcet's disease, along with the approximate percentage of patients who experience them:\n- **Abnormality of temperature regulation**: 90% of patients\n- **Arthritis**: 90% of patients\n- **Meningitis**: 90% of patients\n- **Migraine**: 90% of patients\n- **Myalgia (muscle pain)**: 90% of patients\n- **Nausea and vomiting**: 90% of patients\n- **Orchitis (inflammation of the testicles)**: 90% of patients\n- **Photophobia (sensitivity to light)**: 90% of patients\n- **Vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessels)**: 90% of patients\n- **Abdominal pain**: 50% of patients\n- **Abnormal blistering of the skin**: 50% of patients\n- **Acne**: 50% of patients\n- **Arthralgia (joint pain)**: 50% of patients\n- **Gait disturbance**: 50% of patients\n- **Gastrointestinal hemorrhage**: 50% of patients\n- **Hemiplegia/hemiparesis (weakness on one side of the body)**: 50% of patients\n- **Immunologic hypersensitivity**: 50% of patients\n- **Reduced consciousness/confusion**: 50% of patients\n- **Thrombophlebitis (inflammation of veins)**: 50% of patients\n- **Abnormal pyramidal signs**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the aortic valve**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the endocardium**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the mitral valve**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the myocardium**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the pericardium**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Abnormality of the pleura**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Anorexia**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Arterial thrombosis**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Aseptic necrosis**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Cataract**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Cerebral ischemia**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Coronary artery disease**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Cranial nerve paralysis**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Developmental regression**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Encephalitis**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Gangrene**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Glomerulopathy**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Hemoptysis (coughing up blood)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Hyperreflexia (overactive reflexes)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Incoordination**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Increased intracranial pressure**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Keratoconjunctivitis sicca (dry eyes)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Lymphadenopathy (swollen lymph nodes)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Malabsorption**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Memory impairment**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Myositis (inflammation of muscles)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Pancreatitis (inflammation of the pancreas)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Paresthesia (tingling or numbness)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Polyneuropathy (nerve damage)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Pulmonary embolism (blood clot in the lungs)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Pulmonary infiltrates**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Renal insufficiency (kidney problems)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Retinopathy (eye disease)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Retrobulbar optic neuritis (inflammation of the optic nerve)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Seizures**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Splenomegaly (enlarged spleen)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Vertigo (dizziness)**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Visual impairment**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Weight loss**: 7.5% of patients\n- **Alopecia areata (hair loss)**: Rare\n- **Chorioretinitis (inflammation of the eye)**: Rare\n- **Epididymitis (inflammation of the epididymis)**: Rare\n- **Erythema (skin redness)**: Rare\n- **Genital ulcers**: Rare\n- **Iridocyclitis (inflammation of the iris)**: Rare\n- **Iritis (inflammation of the eye)**: Rare\n- **Irritability**: Rare\n- **Oral ulcer**: Rare\n- **Superficial thrombophlebitis (inflammation of veins)**: Rare\nThe Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) gathers valuable information on how often each sign or symptom occurs in various conditions. Much of this data is sourced from Orphanet, a European database focused on rare diseases. The frequency of a sign or symptom is typically expressed as an estimate of the percentage of patients who exhibit that feature. Sometimes, this information is presented as a fraction, where the first number indicates how many individuals had the symptom and the second number represents the total number of people examined in a study. For instance, a frequency of 25/25 means that all 25 individuals studied exhibited that symptom. It's essential to understand that these frequencies are based on specific studies, so they may differ if another group of patients is examined. In some instances, there may not be enough information available about the frequency of certain symptoms, which could indicate that they are either rare or common. Context recap: Behcet's disease is a complex condition that can affect many parts of the body, leading to a wide range of symptoms. Why this matters: What are the symptoms of Behcet's disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification. Step-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
