          "id": "medquad-chunk-cf0fde7daa2e028b",
          "title": "What is (are) Benign hereditary chorea ?",
          "content": "What is Benign Hereditary Chorea? Benign hereditary chorea (BHC) is a rare movement disorder that usually starts in infancy or early childhood. This condition can affect how a child moves and develops. In infants, some early signs of BHC may include low muscle tone, which means their muscles may feel softer and less firm than usual. They may also have involuntary movements, known as chorea, which are sudden and uncontrollable movements that can make it hard for them to control their bodies. As children grow, they might experience delays in reaching important motor skills milestones, such as crawling or walking. They may also show jerky muscle movements, which are quick, unexpected movements that can happen in different parts of the body. Additionally, some children may develop tics, which are sudden, repetitive movements or sounds that they cannot easily control.\nWhile children with BHC often have normal intelligence, they may encounter challenges in learning and behavior. This means that even though they can think and understand like their peers, they might need extra support in school or at home to help them with their learning. Other signs and symptoms that can occur with BHC include thyroid problems, such as hypothyroidism, which is when the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones, and lung issues, like recurring infections that can make it difficult for them to breathe.\nTreatment for BHC is personalized for each child, which means that doctors will consider the specific needs and symptoms of the child when deciding on the best approach. Some medications, such as tetrabenazine, have been used in individual cases and have shown some success in helping to manage the symptoms of BHC. It is important for families to work closely with healthcare providers to find the most effective treatment plan. BHC is caused by mutations in the NKX2-1 gene, which is also known as the TITF1 gene. This genetic condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent carries the mutation, there is a chance that it can be passed down to their child. Understanding BHC can help families and healthcare providers support children affected by this condition effectively.\nContext recap: What is Benign Hereditary Chorea? Benign hereditary chorea (BHC) is a rare movement disorder that usually starts in infancy or early childhood. This condition can affect how a child moves and develops. In infants, some early signs of BHC may include low muscle tone, which means their muscles may feel softer and less firm than usual.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Benign hereditary chorea ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What is Benign Hereditary Chorea? Benign hereditary chorea (BHC) is a rare movement disorder that usually starts in infancy or early childhood. This condition can affect how a child moves and develops. In infants, some early signs of BHC may include low muscle tone, which means their muscles may feel softer and less firm than usual.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Benign hereditary chorea ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
