          "id": "medquad-chunk-d6d18374b0155b07",
          "title": "What is (are) Benign rolandic epilepsy (BRE) ?",
          "content": "What is Benign Rolandic Epilepsy (BRE)? Benign Rolandic Epilepsy is recognized as the most common type of epilepsy that affects children. It is called 'benign' because most children who have this condition tend to outgrow it by the time they reach puberty, which is usually around the age of 14. This condition is characterized by seizures that specifically affect the rolandic area of the brain. This area is important because it helps control movements in the face and mouth. The seizures associated with Benign Rolandic Epilepsy typically occur during sleep, which can be concerning for both the child and their parents. However, it is important to know that treatment is usually not necessary for this condition. Most children will see a natural resolution of their symptoms as they grow older and their brains develop further. Understanding this condition can help alleviate fears and provide reassurance to families, knowing that it is a common and generally harmless form of epilepsy. If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms or has concerns about seizures, it is always best to consult a healthcare professional for guidance and support. They can provide valuable information and help ensure the well-being of the child as they navigate through this phase of development.\nContext recap: What is Benign Rolandic Epilepsy (BRE)? Benign Rolandic Epilepsy is recognized as the most common type of epilepsy that affects children. It is called 'benign' because most children who have this condition tend to outgrow it by the time they reach puberty, which is usually around the age of 14. This condition is characterized by seizures that specifically affect the rolandic area of the brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Benign rolandic epilepsy (BRE) ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What is Benign Rolandic Epilepsy (BRE)? Benign Rolandic Epilepsy is recognized as the most common type of epilepsy that affects children. It is called 'benign' because most children who have this condition tend to outgrow it by the time they reach puberty, which is usually around the age of 14. This condition is characterized by seizures that specifically affect the rolandic area of the brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Benign rolandic epilepsy (BRE) ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: What is Benign Rolandic Epilepsy (BRE)? Benign Rolandic Epilepsy is recognized as the most common type of epilepsy that affects children. It is called 'benign' because most children who have this condition tend to outgrow it by the time they reach puberty, which is usually around the age of 14. This condition is characterized by seizures that specifically affect the rolandic area of the brain.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Benign rolandic epilepsy (BRE) ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Rare Diseases (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
